-- PJM Western Hub Power Slips as Moderate Weather Cuts Demand
-- B y   C h r i s t i n e   B u u r m a
-- 2013-06-03T20:11:45Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2013-06-03/pjm-western-hub-power-slips-as-moderate-weather-cuts-demand.html
Wholesale electricity on the eastern
U.S. grid operated by PJM Interconnection LLC slipped for the
first time in three days as mild weather cut power demand.  Spot prices covering on-peak hours dropped 18 percent, the
most since May 24. Commodity Weather Group LLC in Bethesda,
 Maryland , predicted mostly normal temperatures on the East Coast
through June 12.  Electricity at PJM’s benchmark Western Hub, which includes
prices from Pennsylvania to Washington, fell $10.97 to $50.84 a
megawatt-hour at 3:12 p.m. from May 31, according to the grid
operator. On-peak hours run from 7 a.m. to 11 p.m.  The high today in Philadelphia may be 80 degrees Fahrenheit
(27 Celsius,) according to  AccuWeather Inc.  in  State College ,
Pennsylvania. The high was 93 degrees on May 31.  PJM predicted  power usage  of 104,600 megawatts at 2:30 p.m.
on the operator’s 13-state grid, which stretches from  New Jersey 
into North Carolina and Illinois. Actual consumption was 104,534
at 2:40 p.m.  New York  City prices fell $8.38, or 14 percent, to $51.22 a
megawatt-hour from the May 31 on-peak average, according to the
 New York Independent System Operator Inc.   On-peak prices  on the six-state grid from Connecticut to
Maine slid $29.21, or 40 percent, to $43.92 a megawatt-hour from
May 31, ISO New England Inc. data showed.  To contact the reporter on this story:
